messages.content:
THOUGHT

The sanitizer report pinpoints a stack-buffer-overflow at `program.c:12` inside `crc8`, reading `buf[i]`. The caller passes `sizeof(buf)` for a 7-byte stack array, so valid indices are `0..6`. The loop in `crc8` is `for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++)`, which executes for `i == len` and reads `buf[7]`, one byte past the end. I confirmed that changing the loop condition to `i < len` makes the program run cleanly under ASan and print a CRC.

ROOT CAUSE: `program.c:11-12`: `crc8` treats `len` as the number of valid bytes but loops with `i <= len`, causing it to process `len + 1` bytes. In `main` (`program.c:22-23`), `buf` has 7 bytes and `crc8(buf, sizeof(buf))` passes `len == 7`; valid indices are `0` through `6`, but the final iteration reads `buf[7]`, producing the ASan stack-buffer-overflow.

LOCAL FIX: Change the CRC loop to stop before `len`:
```diff
 static uint8_t crc8(const uint8_t *buf, size_t len) {
     uint8_t crc = 0x00;
-    for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++) {
+    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
         crc ^= buf[i];
         for (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {
             crc = (crc & 0x80) ? (uint8_t)((crc << 1) ^ 0x07) : (uint8_t)(crc << 1);
         }
     }
```

GLOBAL FIX: Redesign buffer-processing APIs so the bounds invariant is explicit and harder to misuse. For example, use a bounded byte-span/view type (`struct byte_span { const uint8_t *data; size_t size; };`) and implement iteration over `[data, data + size)` centrally, or in C++ use `std::span<const uint8_t>`. Add unit tests for empty, one-byte, and exact-size buffers and keep sanitizers enabled in CI. This prevents the broader class of off-by-one errors where APIs accept a raw pointer and a count but each function hand-rolls its own inclusive/exclusive bound logic.

